nia|44|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Canada|32|chartid=3530|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|56|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Finland|15|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|France|9|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|20|id=2739|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|New Zealand|12|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Norway|10|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Sweden|14|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|31|artist=Pulp|album=This Is Hardcore|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK|1|artist=Pulp|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|114|artist=Pulp|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 January 2017}}\n|}\n\nAs of 2008, sales in the United States have exceeded 86,000 copies, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045824/ask-billboard</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- These are licensed streams for the album, which are allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[http://www.radio3net.ro/dbartists/supersearch/VGhpcyBJcyBIYXJkY29yZSAoSXNsYW5kKQ==/This%20Is%20Hardcore%20%28Island%29 ''This Is Hardcore'']{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ([[Adobe Flash]]) at [[Radio3Net]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n*[http://www.myspace.com/jarviscockerpulp/music/albums/this-is-hardcore-deluxe-edition-2-cd-11603705 ''This Is Hardcore Deluxe Edition (2 CD )''] ([[Adobe Flash]]) at Myspace (streamed copy where licensed)\n<!-- These are licensed streams for the album, which are allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n\n{{Pulp}}\n\n[[Category:Pulp (band) albums]]\n[[Category:1998 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Chris Thomas (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Island Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Olympic Sound Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the album|the song|This Is Hardcore (song)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = This Is Hardcore\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]]\n| cover      = Pulp-This Is Hardcore.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 30 March 1998\n| recorded   = November 1996\u2013January 1998<ref>{{cite book |last=Sturdy |first=Mark |date=15 December 2009 |title=Truth and Beauty: The Story of Pulp |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xYrZx01MPC4C&pg=PT618&lpg=PT618 |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn= 9780857121035 }}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n* [[Townhouse Studios|The Townhouse]], London\n* [[Olympic Studios|Olympic]], London\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[art rock]]<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-hardcore-mw0000035589 This Is Hardcore - Pulp | Songs, Reviews, Credits | AllMusic]</ref>|[[Britpop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/the-10-best-britpop-albums-of-all-time-or-at-least-since-1993-or-so-6633707|title=The 10 Best Britpop Albums of All Time (or At Least Since 1993 or So)|work=The Village Voice|publisher=Suzan Gursoy|author=Laws, Mike|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 69:49\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| producer   = [[Chris Thomas (record producer)|Chris Thomas]]\n| prev_title = [[Countdown 1992\u20131983]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Freshly Squeezed... the Early Years]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = This Is Hardcore\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Help the Aged (song)|Help the Aged]]\n | single1date = 11 November 1997\n | single2     = [[This Is Hardcore (song)|This Is Hardcore]]\n | single2date = 9 March 1998\n | single3     = [[A Little Soul]]\n | single3date = 8 June 1998\n | single4     = [[Party Hard (Pulp song)|Party Hard]]\n | single4date = 7 September 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''This Is Hardcore''''' is the sixth album by English band [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]], first released in March 1998. It came three years after their breakthrough album, ''[[Different Class]]'', and was eagerly anticipated. In 2013, ''[[NME]]'' ranked it at number 166 in its list of [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref>[http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_500_greatest_albums_2013.htm Rocklist.net NME: The 500 Greatest Albums Of All Time : October 2013<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nAs with the band's previous album, ''[[Different Class]]'', it reached No. 1 in the [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/29508/pulp/ |title=Pulp full official chart |publisher=officialcharts.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-07}}</ref> and was well received critically, earning Pulp a third successive nomination for the 1998 [[Mercury Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercuryprize.com/aoty/track.php?TrackID=128 |title=Mercury Prize Shortlist |publisher=mercuryprize.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-07}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent release in the UK later in 1998 came with a bonus live CD entitled \"This Is Glastonbury\". A deluxe edition of ''This Is Hardcore'' was released on 11 September 2006. It contained a second disc of [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]], demos and rarities.\n\nThe cover photo was art directed by [[Peter Saville (graphic designer)|Peter Saville]] and the American painter [[John Currin]] who is known for his figurative paintings of exaggerated female forms. The model photographed is [[Ksenia Sobchak]] and the images were further digitally manipulated by Howard Wakefield who also designed the album.<ref>Cocker, Jarvis [http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1034489,00.html 'They're not grotesque \u2013 they're beautiful'] Retrieved 11 December 2007.</ref> Currin was also the art director for the \"[[Help the Aged (song)|Help the Aged]]\" video, based on his painting \"The Never Ending Story\". Advertising posters showing the album's cover that appeared on the London Underground system were defaced by graffiti artists with slogans like \"This Offends Women\"<ref>Anon [http://www.acrylicafternoons.com/hardcore.html 'PULP \u2013 ACRYLIC AFTERNOONS \u2013 This Is Hardcore] Retrieved 8 July 2008.</ref> and \"This is Sexist\" or \"This is Demeaning\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Amanda|author2=Clay, Alistair|title='Sexist' Pulp ads attacked; Anything goes, say advertisers. Not so, say angry women with spraycans|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=19 April 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe music video for the title track was directed by [[Doug Nichol]] and was listed as the No. 47 best video of all time by ''NME''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/list/100-greatest-music-videos/217342/page/6 |title=100 Greatest Music Videos |publisher=Nme.Com |accessdate=2013-01-07}}</ref>\n\nThe album had first-week sales of just over 50,000, 62% fewer than ''Different Class'' first-week sales of 133,000.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jones |first=Alan |title=The Official UK Charts: Albums - 11 April 1998 |journal=Music Week |date=11 April 1998 |page=18}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-hardcore-mw0000035589 |title=''This Is Hardcore'' \u2013 Pulp |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=30 September 2011 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"Chicago\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-04-03/entertainment/9804030290_1_pulp-glam-midlife |title=Pulp: ''This Is Hardcore'' (Island) |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=3 April 1998 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.ew.com/article/1998/04/13/this-hardcore |title=''This Is Hardcore'' |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=13 April 1998 |accessdate=30 September 2011 |last=Browne |first=David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118113856/http://ew.com/article/1998/04/13/this-hardcore/ |archivedate=18 January 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Confessions of a pop group |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 March 1998 |last=Sullivan |first=Caroline}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"LA\">{{cite news |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1998/apr/05/entertainment/ca-36080 |title=Pulp 'This Is Hardcore' Island |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 April 1998 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |last=Hochman |first=Steve |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828143041/http://articles.latimes.com/1998/apr/05/entertainment/ca-36080 |archivedate=28 August 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = 7/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001323reviews.html |title=Pulp \u2013 ''This Is Hardcore'' |journal=[[NME]] |date=21 March 1998 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |last=Patterson |first=Sylvia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001002145534/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101001323reviews.html |archivedate=2 October 2000 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 7.8/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/21081/Pulp_This_Is_Hardcore |title=Pulp: ''This Is Hardcore'' |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=31 December 1999 |accessdate=30 September 2011 |last=DiCrescenzo |first=Brent |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301171909/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/21081/Pulp_This_Is_Hardcore |archivedate=1 March 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Velvet Overground |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=140 |date=May 1998 |last=Yates |first=Robert}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/pulp/albums/album/302322/review/5946330/this_is_hardcore |title=Pulp: ''This Is Hardcore'' |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=784 |date=23 March 1998 |accessdate=30 September 2011 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603115006/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/pulp/albums/album/302322/review/5946330/this_is_hardcore |archivedate=3 June 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhMpG7hKAr0C&pg=PA133 |title=People's Poet |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=14 |issue=5 |date=May 1998 |accessdate=15 August 2013 |last=Hornby |first=Nick |authorlink=Nick Hornby |page=133}}</ref>\n}}\nThe album was included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=23 March 2010|publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref> The album was very well received in the [[United States of America|States]] with the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', and the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'', all awarding the album three and a half stars out of four.<ref name=\"Chicago\"/><ref name=\"LA\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masley|first1=Ed|title=For the Record|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KLIzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RW8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4011%2C969779|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=12 January 2017|date=22 May 1998}}</ref> In 2014, US [[LGBT]] magazine ''[[Metro Weekly]]'' placed the album at number 46 in its list of the \"50 Best Alternative Albums of the '90s\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/04/50-best-alternative-albums-of-the-90s/|title=50 Best Alternative Albums of the '90s|magazine=[[Metro Weekly]]|last=Gerard|first=Chris|date=4 April 2014|accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> In 2017, ''Pitchfork'' listed the album at number seven in its list \"The 50 Best Britpop Albums.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Britpop Albums|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/10045-the-50-best-britpop-albums/?page=5|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=30 May 2017|date=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics      = [[Jarvis Cocker]]\n| all_music       = Cocker, [[Nick Banks]], [[Candida Doyle]], [[Steve Mackey]] and [[Mark Webber (guitarist)|Mark Webber]], except where noted\n| title1          = The Fear\n| length1         = 5:35\n| title2          = Dishes\n| length2         = 3:30\n| title3          = [[Party Hard (Pulp song)|Party Hard]]\n| length3         = 4:00\n| title4          = [[Help the Aged (song)|Help the Aged]]\n| length4         = 4:28\n| title5          = [[This Is Hardcore (song)|This Is Hardcore]]\n| note5           = includes a sample of \"Bolero on the Moon Rocks\" written by [[Peter Thomas (composer)|Peter Thomas]], recorded by The Peter Thomas Sound Orchestra\n| music5          = {{hlist|Cocker|Banks|Doyle|Mackey|Webber|Thomas}}\n| length5         = 6:25\n| title6          = TV Movie\n| length6         = 3:25\n| title7          = [[A Little Soul]]\n| length7         = 3:19\n| title8        