ame            = yes\n| mapframe_zoom       = 14\n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = \n| extra               = <!-- extra = module = embed = -->\n{{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation1_offname = Burwood rail underbridge\n| designation1_type = State heritage (built)\n| designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n| delisted1_date = \n| designation1_partof = \n| designation1_number = 1030\n| designation1_free1name =  Type\n| designation1_free1value = Railway Bridge/ Viaduct\n| designation1_free2name =  Category\n| designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n| designation1_free3name = Builders\n| designation1_free3value = John Ahern\n}}\n}}\nThe '''Burwood rail underbridge''' is a [[Heritage register|heritage-listed]] [[railway bridge|railway]] [[underbridge]] located on the [[Main Southern railway line, New South Wales|Main Southern]] and [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western]] railway lines in the [[Sydney]] suburb of [[Burwood, New South Wales|Burwood]], in the [[Municipality of Burwood]] local government area of [[New South Wales]], Australia. The triple-girder underbridge spans Burwood Road. The railway bridge was built from 1892 to 1926 by John Ahern. The property is owned by [[RailCorp]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1030>{{cite NSW SHR|5011961|Burwood rail underbridge|hr=01030|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{empty section|date=October 2018}}\n\n== Description ==\nThe Burwood rail underbridge is a single-[[Span (architecture)|span]] {{convert|21.9|m|ft|0|adj=on}} metal, half-through plate web [[girder]]. It carries the double Main Suburban line (middle two of the six tracks) on a three-girder arrangement - outer girder, down suburban, inner girder, up suburban, outer girder. The term \"metal\" has been used to draw attention to the fact that the outer girders were part of an 1892 [[wrought iron]] bridge whereas the 1926 inner girder is steel. The cross girders carry a concrete deck supporting ballasted tracks. On the north side of the Up outer girder is the makers plate - John Ahern 1892 Govt Contract.<ref>Rail Infrastructure s170 Register</ref><ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n=== Condition ===\n\nAs at 27 March 2006, the physical condition is good.<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 27 March 2006, The Burwood rail underbridge is an example of triple-girder bridge. Constructed as a plate web girder bridge, it is a major example of a main line bridge.<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\nBurwood rail underbridge was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Maker's Plate on the triple-girder plate web girder bridge over Burwood Road is historically rare.<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nTriple-girder bridges are relatively rare, there being two others on this rail corridor (located at Burren Street, [[Macdonaldtown, New South Wales|Macdonaldtown]] and Old Canterbury Road, [[Lewisham, New South Wales|Lewisham]]) and another just past [[Strathfield, New South Wales|Strathfield]] over [[Powells Creek (Sydney)|Powells Creek]]. The oldest triple-girder plate web girder bridge is the [[Ultimo Road railway underbridge|1879 wrought iron structure over Ultimo Road]], originally built for the double-track goods line to [[Darling Harbour]] now giving single-track access to the [[Powerhouse Museum]].<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the principal characteristics of a class of cultural or natural places/environments in New South Wales.'''\n\nPlate web girders are a common, basic railway bridge usually with only two parallel girders, be they single or double track bridges. The Burwood rail underbridge represents the triple-girder type.<ref name=nswshr-1030/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nBurwood rail underbridge 1.jpg|Inscription on underbridge: \"John Ahearn 1892 Govt. Contractor\"\nBurwood rail underbridge 2.jpg|View of the underbridge crossing Burwood Rd, Burwood, NSW\nBurwood rail underbridge 3.jpg|View of the underbridge crossing Burwood Rd, Burwood, NSW\nBurwood rail underbridge 4.jpg|Entrance to Burwood Railway Station, situated between 2 of the bridge spans\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Railways|Transport|Engineering}}}}\n*[[Burwood railway station, Sydney]]\n*[[:Category:Railway bridges in New South Wales|Railway bridges in New South Wales]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC|name=Burwood rail underbridge|dno=5011961|id=01030|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Burwood rail underbridge}}\n\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Burwood, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Railway bridges in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1892]]\n[[Category:Main Western railway line, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Main Southern railway line, New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:{{Australian railway bridges|state=autocollapse}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burwood_rail_underbridge"}
{"title_page": "Sunday Best (Surfaces song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sunday Best\n| type       = single\n| artist     = Surfaces\n| album      = Where the Light Is\n| released   = January 8, 2019\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = 2:39\n| label      = {{hlist|TenThousand Projects|[[Caroline Records|Caroline]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|Forrest Frank|Colin Padalecki}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Forrest Frank|Colin Padalecki}}\n| prev_title = Shine on Top\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = Palm Trees\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{external music video|type=single|{{YouTube|83KqwEEGw4|\"Sunday Best\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Sunday Best'''\" is a song by American [[electro-pop]] duo Surfaces, composed of Forrest Frank and Colin Padalecki. The song was released by TenThousand Projects and [[Caroline Records]] on the duo's second album ''Where the Light Is'' on January 8, 2019. The song was re-released as Surfaces' lead single off their third album ''Horizons'' on February 28, 2020''.'' The song's music video was released on July 11, 2019 and it shows the duo turning a boring office to a party place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Surfaces-Shares-New-Music-Video-For-SUNDAY-BEST-20190711|title=Surfaces Shares New Music Video For SUNDAY BEST|date=July 11, 2019|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The song is believed to have gained popularity in late February 2020 on the online-video sharing platform [[TikTok]] for its lyric \"Feeling good, like I should\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/branding/8551350/flighthouse-republic-records-partner-tiktok-series-certified-superfan|title=Flighthouse and Republic Records Partner on New TikTok Series 'Certified Superfan'|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=February 19, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> before it was released for radio airplay in early March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302133607/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|date=March 3, 2020|website=[[All Access]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302133607/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archive-date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.top-charts.com/s/sunday-best-surfaces|title=Sunday Best by Surfaces|website=Top-Charts.com|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The song peaked in the Top 40 in Australia, Canada, Norway, Ireland, New Zealand, the United Kingdom and the United States, as well as the top 100 in Switzerland, Germany and Sweden.\n\n== Live performances ==\nSurfaces made their late-night television debut when they performed the song on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'' on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/03/03/surfaces-perform-on-late-night-with-seth-meyers-first-look/|title=Surfaces Perform \"Sunday Best\" On \"Late Night With Seth Meyers\"|last=Cantor|first=Brian|date=March 3, 2020|website=Headline Planet|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|51|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Best|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|11|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Best|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|18|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Best|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|8