s\n! Goals\n|-\n| [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]\n| [[Daniel Passarella]]\n| 70\n| 23\n|-\n| [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]]\n| [[Diego Maradona]]\n| 91\n| 34\n|}\n\n===Individual records===\n* Most goals scored in all international competitions, including [[Exhibition game#International football|friendlies]]: '''70'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lionel Messi]], 2005\u2013<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/live-scores/copaamerica/news/newsid/280/315/4/|title=Messi & Batistuta react as record changes hands|last=FIFA.com|date=1 January 1900|language=en-GB|access-date=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n* Most goals scored in official international competitions, including [[FIFA World Cup qualification]] and [[FIFA Confederations Cup]]: '''38'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Gabriel Batistuta]], 1991\u20132002\n* Most goals scored in all major international tournaments, not including FIFA World Cup qualification and FIFA Confederations Cup: '''23'''&nbsp;\u2013 Gabriel Batistuta, 1991\u20132002\n* Most goals scored in [[Exhibition game#International football|international friendlies]]: '''34'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013\n* Most goals scored in one calendar year, including friendlies: '''12'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2012; Gabriel Batistuta, 1998\n* Most goals scored in one FIFA World Cup qualification: '''10'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2014]]\n* Most goals scored in all FIFA World Cup qualifications: '''21'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013\n* Most goals scored in one [[FIFA World Cup]] tournament: '''8'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Guillermo St\u00e1bile]], [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]]\n* Most goals scored in all FIFA World Cup tournaments: '''10'''&nbsp;\u2013 Gabriel Batistuta, 1991\u20132001\n* Most goals scored in one FIFA Confederations Cup: '''4'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Luciano Figueroa]], [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005]]\n* Most goals scored in all FIFA Confederations Cup: '''4'''&nbsp;\u2013 Gabriel Batistuta, 1991\u20132002, Luciano Figueroa, 2004\u20132005\n* Most goals scored in one [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]: '''6'''&nbsp;\u2013 Gabriel Batistuta, [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1991]]\n* Most goals scored in all Copas Am\u00e9rica: '''13'''&nbsp;\u2013 Gabriel Batistuta, 1991\u20132002\n* Most goals scored in one South American Championship: '''9'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Humberto Maschio]], [[1957 South American Championship|1957]]\n* Most goals scored in all South American Championships: '''17'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Norberto Doroteo M\u00e9ndez|Norberto M\u00e9ndez]], 1945\u20131956\n* Most goals scored in one [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Football Summer Olympics]]: '''9'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Domingo Tarasconi]], [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928]]\n* Most goals scored in all Football Summer Olympics: '''9'''&nbsp;\u2013 Domingo Tarasconi, 1922\u20131929\n* Most goals scored in all U-20 international competitions, including friendlies: '''18'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2017-2018/lionel-messi-reaches-1-000-goals-as-a-footballer|title=Lionel Messi reaches 1,000 goals as a footballer {{!}} FC Barcelona|website=FC Barcelona|language=en-US|access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Most goals scored in official U-20 international competitions: '''11'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005; [[Javier Saviola]], 2001\n* Most goals scored in one [[FIFA U-20 World Cup]] tournament: '''11'''&nbsp;\u2013 Javier Saviola, [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship|2001]]\n* Most goals scored in all FIFA U-20 World Cup tournaments: '''11'''&nbsp;\u2013 Javier Saviola, 2001\n* Most goals scored in one [[South American Youth Football Championship]]: '''9'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Luciano Galletti]], [[1999 South American U-20 Championship|1999]]; [[Giovanni Simeone]], [[2015 South American Youth Football Championship|2015]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/en/02082015-0108/giovanni-simeone-champion-and-top-scorer|title=Giovanni Simeone is champion and top scorer|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=8 February 2015|access-date=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n* Most goals scored from the [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]: '''13'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013<ref name=\"FIFA\" />\n* Most [[direct free kick]] goals scored in all international competitions, including friendlies: '''6'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], [[Panama national football team|Panama]], [[United States men's national soccer team|USA]], [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n* Most [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-tricks]] scored in all international competitions, including friendlies: '''6'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]], [[Panama national football team|Panama]], [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]], [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]]\n* Most [[Assist (football)|assist]]s provided in all international competitions, including friendlies: '''38'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n* Most assists provided in Copa Am\u00e9rica matches: '''11'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nesn.com/2016/06/lionel-messi-assists-gonzalo-higuains-goal-thrills-gillette-stadium-in-copa-america/ |title= Lionel Messi Sets Copa Am\u00e9rica Assists Record, Thrills Gillette Stadium |publisher= [[New England Sports Network|NESN]] |date=18 June 2016 |accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Most [[Player of the match|Man of the Match]] awards won in one FIFA World Cup: '''4'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]<ref name=\"4MVP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/fourth-mvp-for-leo-messi-at-the-world-cup-finals|title=Fourth MVP for Leo Messi at the World Cup Finals|date=2 July 2014|publisher=FC Barcelona|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Most Man of the Match awards won in FIFA World Cup matches: '''5'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013<ref name=\"4MVP\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=249722/match=300061455/|title=2010 FIFA World Cup&nbsp;\u2013 Matches: Greece vs. Argentina|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Most Man of the Match awards won in one Copa Am\u00e9rica: '''4'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]]<ref name=\"SportES\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/copa-america/messi-cuatro-mvp-cinco-partidos-4319203|title=Messi, cuatro 'MVP' en cinco partidos|date=1 July 2015|language=Spanish|website=Sport.ES|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Most Man of the Match awards won in Copa Am\u00e9rica matches: '''9'''&nbsp;\u2013 Lionel Messi, 2005\u2013<ref name=\"SportES\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2015-2016/america-dazzled-by-mvp-messi|title=America dazzled by MVP Messi {{!}} FCB|website=www.fcbarcelona.com|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n* Oldest player that have ever scored a goal: [[Mart\u00edn Palermo]], 36 years and 7 months old in [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] against [[Greece national football team|Greece]]\n* Oldest player that have scored a goal at FIFA World Cup tournament: Mart\u00edn Palermo, 36 years and 7 months old in 2010 against Greece\n* Youngest player that have ever scored a goal: [[Diego Maradona]], 18 years, 7 months and 4 days old in 1979 against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/match-details/02-06-1979/scotland-argentina/|title=Match Stats|date=22 June 2016}}</ref>\n<!--([[Messi]] scored his first goal when he was 18 years, 8 months and 6 days old)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2006/03/01/world/friendlies/croatia/argentina/361556/|title=Match Stats|date=22 June 2016}}</ref> -->\n* Youngest player that have ever scored a goal at FIFA World Cup tournament: Lionel Messi, 18 years and 357 days old in [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]] against [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]]\n* Youngest player that have ever captained the team at FIFA World Cup tournament: Lionel Messi, 22 years and 363 days old in 2010 against Greece<ref name=\"10years\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/ten-years-with-argentina-for-leo-messi|title=Ten years with Argentina for Leo Messi|date=19 August 2015|publisher=FC Barcelona|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Youngest player to ever reach 100 caps: Lionel Messi, 27 years and 362 days old in 2015 against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]]<ref name=\"10years\" />\n* Youngest player that have scored a goal at South American Championship/Copa America: Diego Maradona 18 years and 10 months old in 1979 against Brazil\n* Only player that have scored against all 9 [[CONMEBOL#Members|South American Nations]]: Lionel Messi, against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]], Brazil, [[Chile national football team|Chile]], Colombia, Ecuador, Paraguay, [[Peru national football team|Peru]], Uruguay, [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport-english.com/en/news/world-football/messis-now-scored-every-south-american-country-except-argentina-4483886|title=Messi's now scored vs. EVERY South American country... except Argentin|last=EN|first=Sport|date=5 September 2015|access-date=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n* Players that have scored the most goals in a match at any competition: '''5'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Manuel Seoane]], in 1925; [[Juan Marvezzi]], in 1941\n* Players that have scored in all 3 matches of the group stage in one FIFA World Cup: [[Oreste Corbatta]], in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]]; Lionel Messi, in 2014<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bubblews.com/posts/messi-broke-record-of-56-years|title=Messi broke record of 56 years|date=25 June 2014|publisher=Bubblews|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019072011/http://www.bubblews.com/posts/messi-broke-record-of-56-years|archivedate=19 October 2015|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Players that have scored the most goals in a match at FIFA World Cup: '''3'''&nbsp;\u2013 Guillermo St\u00e1bile, in 1930; Gabriel Batistuta, in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] & [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]]; [[Gonzalo Higua\u00edn]], in 2010\n* Players that have scored the most goals in a match at South American Championship/Copa Am\u00e9rica: '''5'''&nbsp;\u2013 Manuel Seoane, in [[1925 South American Championship|1925]]; Juan Marvezzi, in 1941\n* Players that have won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Golden Ball]]: Diego Maradona, in [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]]; Lionel Messi, in 2014 \n* Players that have won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|FIFA World Cup Golden Boot]]: Guillermo St\u00e1bile, 8 goals in 1930; [[Mario Kempes]], 6 goals in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]\n* Players that have won the Copa Am\u00e9rica era Golden Shoe: [[Leopoldo Luque]], 4 goals in [[1975 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1975]]; [[Jorge Burruchaga]], 3 goals in [[1983 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1983]]; Gabriel Batistuta, 6 goals in 1991, 4 goals in [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1995]]\n* Players that have won the South American Championship Golden Shoe: [[Julio Libonatti]], 3 goals in [[1921 South American Championship|1921]]; [[:es:Juan Francia|Juan Francia]], 4 goals in [[1922 South American Championship|1922]]; [[:es:Vicente Aguirre|Vicente Aguirre]], 3 goals in [[1923 South American Championship|1923]]; Manuel Seoane, 6 goals in 1925; [[Alfredo Carricaberry]] & [[Segundo Luna]], 7 goals in [[1927 South American Championship|1927]]; [[Herminio Masantonio]], 4 goals in [[1935 South American Championship|1935]]; Juan Marvezzi, 5 goals in 1941; [[Herminio Masantonio]] & [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Moreno]], 7 goals in [[1942 South American Championship|1942]]; Norberto M\u00e9ndez, 6 goals in [[1945 South American Championship|1945]]; [[Rodolfo Micheli]], 8 goals in [[1955 South American Championship|1955]]; Humberto Maschio, 9 goals in 1957; [[Jos\u00e9 Sanfilippo]], 5 goals in [[1959 South American Championship (Ecuador)|1959]]; [[Luis Artime]], 5 goals in [[1967 South American Championship|1967]]\n* Players that have won the Football Summer Olympics Golden Shoe: Domingo Tarasconi, 9 goals in 1928; [[Hern\u00e1n Crespo]], 6 goals in [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]]; [[Carlos Tevez]], 8 goals in [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004]]\n\n==Managers==\nThe first Argentina national team manager was \u00c1ngel V\u00e1zquez, appointed in 1924. [[Guillermo St\u00e1bile]] is the manager with the most matches coaching the team (127).<ref>[http://www.afa.org.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7700:los-cuarenta-nombres-que-dirigieron-la-seleccion-nacional-sp-1379213746&catid=164&Itemid=581&lang=en \"Los 40 nombres que dirigieron la Selecci\u00f3n Nacional\"] on AFA website (1924\u20132006 period listed)</ref> Here is the complete list of managers:<ref>[http://www.mdzol.com/nota/249156-de-olazar-a-batista-43-tecnicos-de-la-seleccion-argentina/ \"De Olazar a Batista: 43 t\u00e9cnicos de la Selecci\u00f3n Argentina\", MDZ online.com] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102044150/http://www.mdzol.com/nota/249156-de-olazar-a-batista-43-tecnicos-de-la-seleccion-argentina/ |date=2 January 2015 }}, 1 November 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1064189-los-42-tecnicos-que-tuvo-la-seleccion \"Los 42 t\u00e9cnicos que tuvo la Selecci\u00f3n\"], ''La Naci\u00f3n''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/arg-intres.html|title=ARGENTINA NATIONAL TEAM ARCHIVE|website=www.rsssf.com}}</ref><ref>[https://www.minutouno.com/notas/3079261-como-pep-guardiola-jose-lago-millan-el-espanol-que-dirigio-la-seleccion Como Pep Guardiola: Jos\u00e9 Lago Mill\u00e1n, el espa\u00f1ol que dirigi\u00f3 a la Selecci\u00f3n] on Minuto Uno, 4 July 2018</ref>\n{|\n|-\n| style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Period\n!Name\n|-\n|1924\u20131925\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} \u00c1ngel V\u00e1zquez\n|-\n|1927\u20131928\n|{{flagicon|SPA|1874}} Jos\u00e9 Lago Mill\u00e1n \n|-\n|1928\u20131929\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Francisco Olazar]]\n|-\n|1929\u20131930\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Francisco Olazar]] and<br />{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Tramutola|Juan J. Tramutola]]\n|-\n|1934\n|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Felipe Pascucci]]\n|-\n|1934\u20131937\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Manuel Seoane]]\n|-\n|1937\u20131939\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} \u00c1ngel Fern\u00e1ndez Roca\n|-\n|1939\u20131958\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Guillermo St\u00e1bile]]\n|-\n|}\n| style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Period\n!Name\n|-\n|1959\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Victorio Spinetto]]\n|-\n|1960\u20131961\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Guillermo St\u00e1bile]]\n|-\n|1962\u20131963\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Juan Carlos Lorenzo]]\n|-\n|1963\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} Alejandro Gal\u00e1n\n|-\n|1963\u20131964\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} Horacio Torres\n|-\n|1964\u20131968\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Minella]]\n|-\n|1968\n|{{flagicon|ITA}}{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Renato Cesarini]]\n|-\n|1968\u20131969\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Humberto Maschio]]\n|-\n|1969\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Adolfo Pedernera]]\n|}\n| style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Period\n!Name\n|-\n|1969\u20131972\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Pizzuti]]\n|-\n|1972\u20131974\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Omar S\u00edvori]]\n|-\n|1974\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Vladislao Cap]]\n|-\n|1974\u20131983\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[C\u00e9sar Luis Menotti]]\n|-\n|1983\u20131990\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Carlos Bilardo]]\n|-\n|1990\u20131994\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Alfio Basile]]\n|-\n|1994\u20131998\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Daniel Passarella]]\n|-\n|1998\u20132004\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Marcelo Bielsa]]\n|-\n|2004\u20132006\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman]]\n|}\n| style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Period\n!Name\n|-\n|2006\u20132008\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Alfio Basile]]\n|-\n|2008\u20132010\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Diego Maradona]]\n|-\n|2010\u20132011\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Sergio Batista]]\n|-\n|2011\u20132014\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Alejandro Sabella]]\n|-\n|2014\u20132016\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Gerardo Martino]]\n|-\n|2016\u20132017\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Edgardo Bauza]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Jorge Sampaoli]]\n|-\n|2018\u2013\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lionel Scaloni]]\n|}\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Brazil===\n{{main|Argentina\u2013Brazil football rivalry}}\nArgentina have a long and fierce rivalry with their South American neighbours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://amp.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/casual-football-fans-emerge-to-pack-out-mcg-for-superclasico-no108/news-story/951729e66c8916c33e6d52952cff0481|title=Casual football fans emerge to pack out MCG for \u2018Superclasico\u2019 No.108|date=10 June 2017|work=Herald Sun}}</ref>\n\n===England===\n{{main|Argentina\u2013England football rivalry}}\nWith a rivalry stemming from the [[1966 World Cup]] and intensified by the [[Falklands War]] of 1982, Argentina and [[England national football team|England]] have had numerous confrontations in World Cup tournaments. Among them was the [[Argentina v England (1986 FIFA World Cup)|quarter-final match]] in [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], where Diego Maradona scored two goals against England. The first was a handball, but was ruled legal by the referee. The second, scored minutes later, saw Maradona passing five England outfield players before scoring, and is often described as one of the greatest goals in football history.\n\nThe nations were paired together in the Round of 16 at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], won by Argentina on penalties, and again at the group stage in [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]], England winning 1\u20130 through a penalty by [[David Beckham]] who had been sent off in the tie four years earlier.\n\n[[File:Germany and Argentina face off in the final of the World Cup 2014 -2014-07-13 (29).jpg|thumb|Action from the [[2014 FIFA World Cup Final]] between Argentina and [[Germany national football team|Germany]]]]\n\n===Germany===\nArgentina have played [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in seven FIFA World Cup matches including three [[FIFA World Cup]] finals: In [[1986 FIFA World Cup Final|1986]] Argentina won 3\u20132, but in [[1990 FIFA World Cup Final|1990]] it was the Germans who were the victors by a 1\u20130 scoreline.\n\nIn [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]] they met for the first time in the group stage, where Argentina suffered a 1-3 loss to [[1954 FIFA World Cup Final|defending champions]] West Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=220/match=1323/live-blog.html|title=1958 FIFA World Cup Sweden \u2122 - Matches|last=FIFA.com|website=FIFA.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> In [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]] both again faced each other in the group stage which ended in a scoreless draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesoccerworldcups.com/head_to_head/argentina_vs_germany.php|title=Argentina vs. Germany Head-to-Head in the World Cups|website=www.thesoccerworldcups.com|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> 2006 they met in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs Argentina|quarter-finals]]; Argentina lost on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw. They met again at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Argentina vs Germany|same stage in 2010]], this time ending with a 4\u20130 victory for Germany. They played each other for the third consecutive World Cup in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|Brazil 2014 event's]] final, where Argentina were defeated [[2014 FIFA World Cup Final|in extra time by a score of 1\u20130]].\n\n===Uruguay===\n{{main|Argentina\u2013Uruguay football rivalry}}\nArgentina have a long-standing rivalry with their neighbors, that came into existence from the early [[Copa Am\u00e9rica|South American Championships]], the [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1930 FIFA World Cup Final|first World Cup final]], held in 1930.\n\nArgentina and Uruguay hold the record for most international matches played between two countries.<ref name=\"First match\"/> The two teams have faced each other 198 times since 1901. The first match between Argentina and Uruguay was also the first official international match to be played outside the United Kingdom.<ref group=\"note\">Although [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] played two internationals in 1885 and 1886, neither match is considered official; Canada did not play an official international until 1904 and the USA did not play one until 1916.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Nigeria===\nA minor rivalry developed from the 1990s between Argentina and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], based not on geographical proximity, long-term battles for honours or factors outside football, but due to the frequency of significant matches between them.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/nigeria-argentina-a-rivalry-that-keeps-on-runnng-2384741| title = Nigeria-Argentina: A rivalry that keeps on running | publisher = [[FIFA]] | date = 25 June 2014 | accessdate = 28 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=sick>{{Cite web | url = https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2018/6/26/17507812/nigeria-argentinia-world-cup-rivalry | title = Nigeria always loses to Argentina and I'm sick of it| publisher = [[SB Nation]] | date = 26 June 2018 | accessdate = 28 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.eluniverso.com/deportes/2017/12/01/nota/6506806/argentina-vs-nigeria-clasico-mundiales-cuenta-pendiente-africanos| title = Argentina vs. Nigeria, un cl\u00e1sico en los Mundiales con cuenta pendiente para los africanos|trans-title=Argentina vs. Nigeria, a classic in the World Cup with the Africans still to open their account | publisher = [[El Universo]] |language=es | date = 1 December 2017| accessdate = 29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://segundoenfoque.com/desde-hace-cuanto-viene-la-rivalidad-entre-argentina-y-nigeria-2018-06-27| title = \u00bfDesde hace cu\u00e1nto viene la rivalidad entre Argentina y Nigeria?|trans-title=How long has there been a rivalry between Argentina and Nigeria?| publisher = [[Segundo Enfoque]] |language=es | date = 27 June 2018 | accessdate = 29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.diariopublicable.com/futbol/2521-nigeria--un-viejo-conocido-de-argentina.html| title = Nigeria, un viejo conocido de Argentina|trans-title=Nigeria, an old acquaintance of Argentina | publisher = [[Diario Publicable]] |language=es | date = 23 June 2014 | accessdate = 29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.guioteca.com/futbol-argentino/argentina-vs-nigeria-el-historial-le-da-esperanzas-a-los-hinchas-albicelestes/| title = Argentina vs. Nigeria: El historial le da esperanzas a los hinchas \"albicelestes\"|trans-title=Argentina vs. Nigeria: History gives hope to \"albiceleste\" fans | publisher = [[Guioteca]] |language=es | date = 26 June 2018 | accessdate = 29 June 2018}}</ref> This has included five World Cup group games, all won by Argentina by a single goal margin: [[1994 FIFA World Cup Group D#Argentina vs Nigeria|2\u20131 in 1994]], [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F#Argentina vs Nigeria|1\u20130 in 2002]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group B#Argentina vs Nigeria|1\u20130 in 2010]], [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group F#Nigeria vs Argentina|3\u20132 in 2014]] and [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group D#Nigeria vs Argentina|2\u20131 in 2018]]. The fixture is the most common in the competition's history involving an African nation,<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://qz.com/1313640/world-cup-2018-nigeria-v-argentina-for-the-fifth-time-photos/| title = Photos of the 24-year soccer rivalry between Nigeria and Argentina | publisher = [[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] | date = 26 June 2018 | accessdate = 28 June 2018}}</ref> and has occurred in five of the six tournaments for which Nigeria has qualified. The sides also met in the [[1995 King Fahd Cup]] (the predecessor to the Confederations Cup) as champions of their respective continents, drawing 0\u20130. \n\nBelow full international level, their [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic teams]] also faced off in the gold medal match in [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament#Gold Medal match|1996 (3\u20132 to Nigeria)]], and [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament#Gold medal match|2008 (1\u20130 to Argentina)]]. The final of the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]] was also played between them; both Argentina goals in their 2\u20131 win were scored by [[Lionel Messi]], who would go on to find the net for the senior team in the 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/06/25/sports/worldcup/world-cup-nigeria-vs-argentina.html|title=World Cup 2014: Argentina Defeats Nigeria, 3\u20132|last=Klein|first=Jeff|date=25 June 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=28 June 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012202612/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/06/25/sports/worldcup/world-cup-nigeria-vs-argentina.html|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and 2018<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/43974672| title = Nigeria 1-2 Argentina | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 26 June 2018 | accessdate = 28 June 2018}}</ref> World Cup fixtures. On 6 September 2011, Bangabandhu National Stadium hosted an international friendly football match between the full-strength Argentina and Nigeria teams, featuring Lionel Messi, Sergio Ag\u00fcero, Javier Mascherano and John Obi Mikel among the other star players of both nations. Argentina won 3\u20131 with goals from then-Real Madrid teammates Gonzalo Higua\u00edn and \u00c1ngel Di Mar\u00eda, and an own goal from Nigeria's Elderson Echi\u00e9jil\u00e9 with Chinedu Obasi scoring Nigeria's lone goal.\n\nThe sense of rivalry is more keenly felt on the Nigerian side, as Argentina have won almost all of their encounters and have more important traditional opponents to concentrate on, in contrast to the West Africans who remain keen to finally overcome a more illustrious foe.<ref name=sick/>\n\n==Honours==\n===Competitive===\n'''[[FIFA World Cup]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Champions (2)''': [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]], [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]]\n* {{silver02}} Runners-up (3): [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]], [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]], [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]\n\n'''[[Copa Am\u00e9rica|South American Championship / Copa Am\u00e9rica]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Champions (14)''': [[1921 South American Championship|1921]], [[1925 South American Championship|1925]], [[1927 South American Championship|1927]], [[1929 South American Championship|1929]], [[1937 South American Championship|1937]], [[1941 South American Championship|1941]], [[1945 South American Championship|1945]], [[1946 South American Championship|1946]], [[1947 South American Championship|1947]], [[1955 South American Championship|1955]], [[1957 South American Championship|1957]], [[1959 South American Championship (Argentina)|1959 (Argentina)]], [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1991]], [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993]]\n* {{silver02}} Runners-up (14): [[1916 South American Championship|1916]], [[1917 South American Championship|1917]], [[1920 South American Championship|1920]], [[1923 South American Championship|1923]], [[1924 South American Championship|1924]], [[1926 South American Championship|1926]], [[1935 South American Championship|1935]], [[1942 South American Championship|1942]], [[1959 South American Championship (Ecuador)|1959 (Ecuador)]], [[1967 South American Championship|1967]], [[2004 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2004]], [[2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2007]], [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]]\n* {{bronze03}} Third place (5): [[1919 South American Championship|1919]], [[1956 South American Championship|1956]], [[1963 South American Championship|1963]], [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1989]], [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2019]]\n* Fourth place (2): [[1922 South American Championship|1922]], [[1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1987]]\n\n'''[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Champions (1)''': [[1992 King Fahd Cup|1992]]\n* {{silver02}} Runners-up (2): [[1995 King Fahd Cup|1995]], [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005]]\n\n'''[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Gold medal (2)''': [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004]], [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]]\n* {{silver02}} Silver medal (2): [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|1928]], [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996]]\n\n'''[[Panamerican Championship]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Champions (1)''': [[1960 Panamerican Championship|1960]]\n* {{silver02}} Runners-up (1): [[1956 Panamerican Championship|1956]]\n\n'''[[Artemio Franchi Trophy|Intercontinental Cup of Nations]]'''\n* '''{{gold01}} Champions (1)''': [[Artemio Franchi Trophy#1993|1993]]\n\n===Friendly===\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Newton Cup]]{{refn|group=note|name=afaauf}} (17):''' 1906, 1907, 1908, 1909, 1911, 1916, 1918, 1924, 1927, 1928, 1937, 1942, 1945, 1957, 1973, 1975, 1976\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Copa Lipton|Lipton Cup]]{{refn|Organised by [[Argentine Football Association|Argentine]] and [[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguayan]] Associations|group=note|name=afaauf}} (18):''' 1906, 1907, 1908, 1909, 1913, 1915, 1916, 1917, 1918, 1928, 1937, 1942, 1945, 1957, 1962, 1968, 1976, 1992\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Roca Cup]]{{refn|Organised by [[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazilian]] and [[Argentine Football Association|Argentine]] Associations|group=note|name=afacbf}} (4):''' [[Roca Cup|1923]], [[Roca Cup|1939\u201340]], [[Roca Cup|1940]], [[Roca Cup|1971]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesr/roca.html |title=Copa Julio Roca at RSSSF |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Supercl\u00e1sico de las Am\u00e9ricas]]{{refn|group=note|name=afacbf}} (2):''' [[2017 Supercl\u00e1sico de las Am\u00e9ricas|2017]], [[2019 Supercl\u00e1sico de las Am\u00e9ricas|2019]]\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Ta\u00e7a das Na\u00e7\u00f5es|Nations\u00b4 Cup]]{{refn|Organised by the [[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazilian Confederation]]|group=note|name=cbf}} (1):''' [[Ta\u00e7a das Na\u00e7\u00f5es|1964]]\n* '''{{gold01}} [[Kirin Cup]]{{refn|Organised by Japanese [[Kirin Company]]|group=note|name=kirin}} (1):''' [[Kirin Cup#1992 Kirin Cup|1992]], [[Kirin Cup#2003 Kirin Cup|2003]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Association football|Argentina}}\n* [[List of Argentina international footballers]]\n* [[Argentina national football team head to head]]\n* [[Argentina national under-23 football team]]\n* [[Argentina national under-20 football team]]\n* [[Argentina national under-17 football team]]\n* ''[[Vamos, vamos, Argentina]]''\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|2|group=note}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Argentina national association football team|Argentina national football team}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.afa.com.ar/}} {{in lang|es}}\n* [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=arg/index.html Argentina FIFA profile]\n\n{{Argentina national football team}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle=background:#6AB5FF;color:#ffffff;border:1px solid #00355E ;|list1=\n{{Argentina national football team matches}}\n{{Argentina national football team squads}}\n{{Argentina national football team managers}}\n{{FIFA World Cup winners}}\n{{Copa Am\u00e9rica winners}}\n{{FIFA Confederations Cup winners}}\n{{Football in Argentina}}\n{{CONMEBOL teams}}\n{{National sports teams of Argentina}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Argentina National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Argentina national football team| ]]\n[[Category:FIFA Confederations Cup-winning countries]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning countries]]\n[[Category:South American national association football teams]]\n[[Category:Football teams in Argentina]]\n", "name_user": "SpinnDoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentina_national_football_team"}
